================================================================================
PRIOR ART AND CONCEPTUAL INFLUENCES
================================================================================

Stavr was developed independently. The following acknowledgments document
overlapping or adjacent work in the same problem space; Stavr does not
incorporate source code from any of them unless explicitly noted.

Trust-scope primitive
---------------------
Stavr's trust-scope concept -- named, time-bounded, action-capped, revocable
approval envelopes for autonomous agents -- shares conceptual ground with the
Tessera Protocol, an Apache-2.0 project at
https://github.com/tessera-protocol/tessera that describes a capability-based
authority layer for AI agents. Stavr and Tessera are independent implementations.
Stavr positions itself around a broader scope (BOM-driven planning, connector
bus, cost routing, executor) of which trust scopes are one primitive among many.

Model Context Protocol
----------------------
Stavr's daemon implements MCP (Model Context Protocol) on the wire and consumes
the official TypeScript SDK at https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/typescript-sdk
(MIT). The MCP specification and SDK are products of Anthropic and the MCP
community; Stavr is not affiliated with or endorsed by Anthropic.

Design language references
--------------------------
- The "ESB bus" framing in the Toolkit dashboard is a generic enterprise-
  service-bus metaphor; no specific commercial ESB product is referenced.
- The Topology dashboard's visual style is inspired by network management UIs
  (Unifi, FlightRadar24); no source or assets are copied from those products.
- "LEGO" and "DUPLO" are used as common-noun metaphors for kit-of-parts assembly
  and are not affiliated with, endorsed by, or sponsored by the LEGO Group.

================================================================================
NAME AND AFFILIATIONS
================================================================================

The name "stavr" derives from the Old Norse word for a staff, stake, or rune-
stave (Proto-Germanic *stabaz, cognate with English "staff"). The name is used
here for its evocative meaning around inscription and audit, not as a claim of
exclusive use.

Stavr is not affiliated with, endorsed by, or sponsored by:
- the STAVR Team blockchain validator operation at stavr.tech (proof-of-stake
  validator infrastructure across Cosmos / Solana / Polkadot / Ethereum ecosystems),
- the Tessera Protocol project (referenced above),
- Anthropic, the LEGO Group, Ubiquiti / Unifi, or FlightRadar24,
- or any other entity sharing a similar name or working in adjacent domains.

